default&#xa0;default2.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultINNS cost the British economy at least £1.7billion every year, and it is estimated that in addition, 
default‘
defaultthe total non-market costs incurred, including disturbance of ecosystem services, have been estimated to £96 billion in the UK
default’.
default 
defaultT
defaulthe European Environment Agency (EEA) has estimated that the cost to the EU of a range of INNS was 
defaultat least 
default€
default12billion per year.
default All the evidence points to these costs to society increasing significantly and exponentially, as invasion increases and established INNS become more invasive (or the impacts of their invasiveness manifest themselves). The Millennium Ecosystem Assessment asserted that the global negative impacts of INNS on biodiversity were of a similar magnitude to that of climate change and habitat loss.
